addr="jms-00I7">Relations</fr:link> in program specification</fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>17</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
href="jonmsterling.xml"
type="local"
addr="jonmsterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author><fr:contributor><fr:link
href="marcelofiore.xml"
type="local"
addr="marcelofiore">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link></fr:contributor></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>In the simplest terms, a specification of a program is a <fr:link
href="jms-00I7.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00I7">relation</fr:link> that describes the possible input/output pairs that can occur. For example, the specification that a given program compute the square root is captured by the <fr:link
href="jms-00I7.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00I7">relation</fr:link> <fr:tex>\mathsf {sq}  \colon   \mathbb {R}_{ \geq  0}  \mathbin { \nrightarrow }   \mathbb {R}</fr:tex> given by pairs <fr:tex>{ \mathopen {} \left ( x,y \right ) \mathclose {}}</fr:tex> such that <fr:tex>x = y^2</fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="true"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>3069</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon><fr:addr>jms-00IA</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00IA.xml</fr:route><fr:title><fr:link
href="jms-00I7.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00I7">Relations</fr:link> in operational semantics</fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>17</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
href="jonmsterling.xml"
type="local"
addr="jonmsterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex>E</fr:tex> represent the set of states in a machine; then the behavior of this machine is usually described by a pair of <fr:link
href="jms-00I7.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00I7">relations</fr:link> <fr:tex>S  \colon  E \mathbin { \nrightarrow }  E</fr:tex> and <fr:tex>V \colon  E \mathbin { \nrightarrow }   { \mathopen {} \left \{ \star \right \} \mathclose {}}</fr:tex>, such that <fr:tex>e \mathrel {S} e'</fr:tex> when it is possible for the machine to transition from state <fr:tex>e</fr:tex> to <fr:tex>e'</fr:tex> and such that <fr:tex>e \mathrel {V}  \star</fr:tex> when the machine can halt in state <fr:tex>e</fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="true"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>3071</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon><fr:addr>jms-00IB</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00IB.xml</fr:route><fr:title><fr:link
href="jms-00I7.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00I7">Relations</fr:link> in program typing</fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>17</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
href="jonmsterling.xml"
type="local"
addr="jonmsterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author><fr:contributor><fr:link
href="marcelofiore.xml"
type="local"
addr="marcelofiore">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link></fr:contributor></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex>E</fr:tex> be the set of expression in a given programming language, and let <fr:tex>T</fr:tex> be the set of types in that programming language. Then the property of a given program having a certain type forms a <fr:link
href="jms-00I7.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00I7">relation</fr:link> <fr:tex>E \mathbin { \nrightarrow }  T</fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
